Newton’s Law of Cooling  
T(t) = T_env  + (T₀ – T_env) e^{kt}, t in minutes  

Environment (refrigerator) temperature: T_env = 35 °F  
Initial soda temperature (t = 0): T₀ = 71 °F  

1.  Find k from the 10-minute reading  
 T(10) = 63 °F  

 63 = 35 + (71 – 35) e^{10k}  
 63 = 35 + 36 e^{10k}  
 28 = 36 e^{10k}  
 e^{10k} = 28/36 = 7/9  
 k = ln(7/9) / 10 ≈ –0.0251

2.  Model for any time t (minutes)  
 T(t) = 35 + 36 e^{(ln(7/9)/10)t}  
  = 35 + 36 (7/9)^{\,t/10}

3.  Temperature after one hour (t = 60 min)  
 T(60) = 35 + 36 (7/9)^{6}  

 (7/9)^{6} ≈ 0.221 → 36 × 0.221 ≈ 7.96  

 T(60) ≈ 35 + 7.96 ≈ 42.9 °F  

To the nearest degree, the soda will be about 43 °F after one hour.
